is a web component that is deployed on the server to create dynamic web page.", "pages": [3], "end_pos": 945, "summary": "Defines servlet as a dynamic web component and lists major web containers including GlassFish as course standard.", "start_pos": 413, "chunk_type": "definition_and_examples", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_002"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": []}, {"id": "CHUNK_004", "text": "What Is a Servlet? Servlet is a technology used to create web application. Servlet is a class that extend the capabilities of the servers and respond to the incoming request. It can respond to any type of requests. Servlet is a web component that is deployed on the server to create dynamic web page.\n\nWeb container interacts with Jakarta Servlets. \nA web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets, mapping a URL to a particular servlet and ensuring that the URL requester has the correct access-rights.", "pages": [4], "end_pos": 1370, "summary": "Reiterates servlet definition and explicitly states web container responsibilities: lifecycle, URL mapping, and access control.", "start_pos": 946, "chunk_type": "definition", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_002"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": []}, {"id": "CHUNK_005", "text": "Web container * Web container interacts with Jakarta Servlets. ¢ A web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets, mapping a URL to a particular servlet and ensuring that the URL requester has the correct access-rights.", "pages": [5], "end_pos": 1575, "summary": "Concise restatement of web container’s core responsibilities toward servlets.", "start_pos": 1371, "chunk_type": "definition", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_002"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": []}, {"id": "CHUNK_006", "text": "The Container will give you the following Communications support - The container provides an easy way for your servlets to talk to your web server. Lifecycle Management - The container controls the life and death of the serviet, It takes care of loading the classes, instantiating and initializing the servlets, invoking the servlets methods and making servlet instances eligible for garbage collection, it also takes care of resources management. Multithreading Support - The Container automatically creates a new Java thread for every servlet request it receives, there are still issues around synchronization but having the server create and manage the treads for multiple requests still saves you a lot of wor’ Declarative Security - With a Container you get to use an XML deployment descriptor to configure (and modify) security without having to hard-code it into your servlet class code, thus you don''t have to recompile your va source files. JSP Support - The Container takes core of translating JSP into real Java.", "pages": [6], "end_pos": 2458, "summary": "Enumerates key services provided by web containers: communications, lifecycle, threading, declarative security, and JSP support.", "start_pos": 1576, "chunk_type": "feature_list", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_002"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_004"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_007", "text": "How web server handle a request? When a web server gets a request for a servlet, the web server hands the request to the Container in which the servlet is deployed. It''s the Container that gives the servlet the HTTP request and response and it''s the Container that calls the servlet''s methods (doPost() and doGet()).", "pages": [7], "end_pos": 2742, "summary": "Outlines high-level delegation flow: web server → container → servlet invocation.", "start_pos": 2459, "chunk_type": "process_summary", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_003"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_002"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_008", "text": "How the Container handles a request for a servlet 1. The user clicks a link that has a URL to a servlet instead of a static page 2. The container \"sees\" that the request is for a servlet, so the container creates two objects HttpServiletResponse and HttpServletRequest 3. The container finds the correct servlet based on the URL in the request, creates or allocates a thread for that request and passes the request and response Objects to the servlet thread 4. The container calls the servliet''s service() method, depending on the type of request, the service() methods calls either the doGet() or doPost() method 5. The doGet() method generates the dynamic page and arranges the page into the response object. Remember, the container still has a reference to the response object 6. The thread completes, the container converts the response object into an HTTP response, send it back to the client, then deletes the request and response objects.", "pages": [8], "end_pos": 3517, "summary": "Six-step detailed description of servlet request handling, emphasizing object creation, thread allocation, method dispatch, and response serialization.", "start_pos": 2743, "chunk_type": "stepwise_process", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_003"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_006", "CONC_007"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_009", "text": "Step 1 ¢ The user clicks a link that has a URL to a servlet instead of a static page Jeez\n\nThe container \"sees\" that the request is for a servlet, so the container creates two objects HttpServietResponse and HttpServietRequest\n\nThe container finds the correct servlet based on the URL in the request, creates or allocates a thread for that request and passes the request and response Objects to the servlet thread\n\nThe container calls the servlet''s service() method, depending on the type of request, the service() methods calls either the doGet() or doPost() method\n\nThe doGet() method generates the dynamic page and puts the page into the response object. Remember, the container still has a reference to the response object\n\nStep 6 ° The doGet() method generates the dynamic page and stuffs the page into the response object. Remember, the | ae 0 Container still has a reference to the eis ae arte ie cn", "pages": [9], "end_pos": 4214, "summary": "Annotated step-by-step breakdown of servlet request flow, reinforcing object creation, dispatch, and response binding.", "start_pos": 3518, "chunk_type": "annotated_steps", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_003"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_006", "CONC_007"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_010", "text": "How to find the correct servlet « Use @WebServiet annotation in Servlet 3.0 in Java EE6. * Prior to Servlet 3.0, you need to register the Serviet using deployment descriptor( web.xm/) by employing <serv/et> or <serviet-mapping> tags.\n\nA can have three names Client-Known URL name - The client sees a URL for the servlet but does not know how that servlet name maps to a real directory and file back on the server, the URL is a fake name made up for the clients * Deployer-Known Secret Internal name - The deployer can create a name that''s known only to the deployer and others in the real operational environment, this name again is a fake name made up just for the deployment of the servlet * Actual filename - The developers servlet class has a fully-qualified name that includes both the class name and package name. The class file has a real path and file name, depending on where the package directory structure lives on the server.", "pages": [10], "end_pos": 4952, "summary": "Explains servlet naming layers (client URL, internal name, fully-qualified class) and mapping mechanisms: @WebServlet vs web.xml.", "start_pos": 4215, "chunk_type": "mapping_explanation", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_004"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_011", "text": "Naming and Mapping Servlets By mapping the name instead of coding in the real file and path name you have the flexibility to move things around without having the maintenance nightmare of tracking down and change client code that refers to the old location of the servlet files, also by mapping the filename you can hide the real directories, thus increasing security.\nWhen you deploy your servlet into your Web Container, you will tell the Container how to run your servlets and JP. To map URLs to servlets - one to map the client-known public URL name to your own internal name, and the other to map your own internal name to a fully-qualified class name.", "pages": [11], "end_pos": 5487, "summary": "Justifies URL mapping benefits: deployment flexibility, maintainability, and security through abstraction.", "start_pos": 4953, "chunk_type": "rationale", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_004"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_002"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_012", "text": "Each of these methods accepts two input parameters. \nFirst object type - HttpServletRequest, which contains the client’s request data and methods to retrieve it. \nSecond object type - HttpServletResponse, into which your response to the request is written. When your servlet finishes executing,  Web container transmits the data contained in this object back to the client.", "pages": [12], "end_pos": 5830, "summary": "Defines HttpServletRequest and HttpServletResponse as mandatory servlet method parameters and explains their roles.", "start_pos": 5488, "chunk_type": "interface_definition", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_006"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_003"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_013", "text": "In line 11 we use a method of the HttpServletResponse object to set the content type of the response that we are going to send. All response headers must be set before a PrintWriter or ServletOutputStream is requested to write body data to the response.\nIn line 12 we request a PrintWriter object to write text to the response message.\nIn lines 13 and 14 we use the PrintWriter to write the text of type text/html (as specified through the content-type).\nThe PrintWriter gets closed in line 15 when we are finished writing to it.", "pages": [13], "end_pos": 6212, "summary": "Details HttpServletResponse usage: header setting order, PrintWriter acquisition, HTML generation, and resource cleanup.", "start_pos": 5831, "chunk_type": "implementation_detail", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_006"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_014", "text": "Servlet Demonstration\n\nService()\nHandles the setup and dispatching of doXXX()\ndoGet()\nHandle GET class\nExample: a document or an html page \nAdditional information (or, a query string) can be appended to the GET method to refine the request \ndoPost()\nHandle POST request\nExample: a credit card number, new data to be stored \nSometimes megabytes of information can be sent \nOther predefined methods: doHead(), doTrace(), doOptions()", "pages": [14], "end_pos": 6611, "summary": "Documents HttpServlet’s standard methods, distinguishing doGet() (safe, idempotent) and doPost() (state-changing, large payload).", "start_pos": 6213, "chunk_type": "method_reference", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_007"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_015", "text": "Things You Do in doGet() & doPost() Extract client-sent information (HTTP parameter) from HTTP request ° Set (Save) and get (read) attributes to/from Scope objects ° Perform some business logic or access database * Optionally forward the request to other Web components (Servlet or JSP) * Populate HTTP response message and send it to client ° In practice, the distinction in the use of GET and POST has been blurred, since complicated requests may need to send more data than a GET can support so that POST is used instead", "pages": [15], "end_pos": 7029, "summary": "Lists common tasks inside doGet()/doPost(): parameter extraction, scope manipulation, business logic, forwarding, and response population.", "start_pos": 6612, "chunk_type": "functional_specification", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_007"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_006"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_016", "text": "Examples - Servlet Handles Form Data ° Text box ¢ Radio button ¢ Checkbox\n\nText Box “T Et eer ees ra t Introduction é By.Customize Links. [) Suggested Sites Web Slice Gallery € > G (© tocathost3080/3_ SERVLET_DEMO/texthtm! DQ % & 6 a | Other bookmarks\n€ > S [O localhost8080/3_SERVLET_OEMO/texthtml O) D) SuggestedStes D) Web Stice Gattery $C Otherbootmnarts, Pate ean |]\n<%@page contentType=\"text/html\" pageEncoding=\"UTF-8\"%>\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n    <head>\n        <title>Introduction</title>\n    </head>\n    <body>\n        <form method=\"get\" action=\"hello\">\n            please enter your name:\n            <input type=text name=\"name\">\n            <p><input type=\"submit\">\n        </form>\n    </body>\n</html>", "pages": [16], "end_pos": 7628, "summary": "Introduces form data types and provides HTML example for text input with GET submission.", "start_pos": 7030, "chunk_type": "example_form", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_009"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_017", "text": "<%@page contentType=\"text/html\" pageEncoding=\"UTF-8\"%>\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head>\n  <title>Radio Button</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <form  method=\"get\"  action=\"radio\" >   \n        <br>How many employees in your company?<br>\n        <br>1-100<input type=\"radio\" name=\"employee\" value=\"1-100\" />\n        <br>100-200<input type=\"radio\" name=\"employee\" value=\"100-200\" />\n        <br>200-300<input type=\"radio\" name=\"employee\" value=\"200-300\"/>\n        <br>300-400<input type=\"radio\" name=\"employee\" value=\"300-400\"/>\n        <br>500-more<input type=\"radio\" name=\"employee\" value=\"500-more\"/>\n     <br/><input type=\"submit\">\n  </form>\n</body>\n</html>", "pages": [17], "end_pos": 8049, "summary": "HTML form example demonstrating radio button usage with shared ''name'' attribute.", "start_pos": 7629, "chunk_type": "example_form", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_009"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_018", "text": "<%@page contentType=\"text/html\" pageEncoding=\"UTF-8\"%>\n<!DOCTYPE html><html>\n    <head>\n        <title>check box</title>\n    </head>\n    <body>\n        <form method=get action=\"/lab3/checkbox\">\n            <br/>what ides do you use?<br>\n            <br/>Netbean <input type=\"checkbox\" name=\"ide\" value=\"netbean\" >\n            <br/>Jdeveloper <input type=\"checkbox\" name=\"ide\" value=\"jdeveloper\"/>\n            <br/>Eclipse?<input type=\"checkbox\" name=\"ide\"  value=\"eclipse\" />\n            <p><input type=\"submit\">\n        </form>\n    </body>\n</html>", "pages": [18], "end_pos": 8423, "summary": "HTML form example illustrating checkbox group with same ''name'' and distinct ''value'' attributes.", "start_pos": 8050, "chunk_type": "example_form", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_009"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005"]}], "concepts": [{"id": "CONC_001", "title": "Servlet", "aliases": ["HTTP servlet", "Java servlet"], "keywords": ["Jakarta Servlet", "HTTP handler", "server-side Java"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 3, "description": "A servlet is a Java class that extends server capabilities to handle client requests dynamically. It is a web component deployed in a web container, conforming to the Jakarta Servlet specification. Servlets respond to HTTP requests (e.g., GET, POST) by implementing methods like doGet() or doPost(), and they generate dynamic content—typically HTML—by writing to an HttpServletResponse object. Servlets are managed entirely by the container, which handles lifecycle, threading, security, and request-response binding. They require no direct socket programming and abstract low-level network concerns, enabling developers to focus on business logic.", "concept_type": "component", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_003", "CHUNK_004"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_002", "CONC_005", "CONC_007"]}, {"id": "CONC_002", "title": "Web Container", "aliases": ["Servlet container"], "keywords": ["servlet container", "Jakarta EE container", "runtime environment"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 3, "description": "A web container is a runtime environment that manages Jakarta servlets and JSPs within a Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE) application server. It provides essential services including servlet lifecycle management (loading, instantiation, initialization, garbage collection), URL-to-servlet mapping, multithreaded request handling, declarative security via deployment descriptors or annotations, JSP translation, and communication support between servlets and the underlying web server. Examples include Tomcat, GlassFish, WildFly, WebLogic, and WebSphere. The container acts as an intermediary between the HTTP server and servlet code, invoking service(), doGet(), or doPost() based on request type.", "concept_type": "component", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_003", "CHUNK_005", "CHUNK_006"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_004", "CONC_008"]}, {"id": "CONC_003", "title": "HTTP Request-Response Lifecycle", "aliases": ["servlet request flow", "HTTP handling sequence"], "keywords": ["request dispatch", "thread per request", "service lifecycle"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 4, "description": "The HTTP request-response lifecycle describes the end-to-end flow from client browser submission to server response delivery. It begins when a user clicks a link targeting a servlet URL; the web server delegates the request to the web container. The container creates HttpServletRequest and HttpServletResponse objects, locates the mapped servlet, allocates a thread, invokes service(), which dispatches to doGet() or doPost() based on method. The servlet processes input, executes business logic, populates the response, and returns control. Finally, the container serializes the response into HTTP format and transmits it back to the client. Thread cleanup and object disposal follow completion.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_007", "CHUNK_008", "CHUNK_009"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_002", "CONC_006"]}, {"id": "CONC_004", "title": "URL Mapping", "aliases": ["servlet registration", "endpoint binding"], "keywords": ["@WebServlet", "web.xml", "servlet mapping", "deployment descriptor"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 3, "description": "URL mapping is the mechanism that binds client-visible URLs to internal servlet names and ultimately to fully qualified Java class names. It decouples public endpoint naming from physical deployment, enabling flexibility and security. Two layers exist: (1) client-known URL name (e.g., ''/firstServlet'') mapped to a deployer-known internal name (e.g., ''MyServlet''), and (2) internal name mapped to a class (e.g., ''ict.servlet.MyServlet''). Mapping is achieved either declaratively via web.xml (<servlet> and <servlet-mapping>) or programmatically using @WebServlet annotation (introduced in Servlet 3.0). This abstraction prevents hardcoding paths and supports refactoring without breaking client integrations.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_010", "CHUNK_011"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_002", "CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CONC_005", "title": "HttpServletRequest", "aliases": ["HTTP request"], "keywords": ["request object", "form data extraction", "HTTP parameter"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 3, "description": "HttpServletRequest is a Jakarta Servlet interface representing an HTTP request received by a servlet. It encapsulates client metadata—including HTTP method, headers, query parameters, form data, cookies, session information, and input streams—and provides methods to extract this data (e.g., getParameter(), getParameterValues(), getHeader(), getSession()). It serves as the primary conduit for retrieving user-submitted information such as form fields (text boxes, radio buttons, checkboxes) and enables stateful interaction through scoped attributes and session tracking. Its immutability and container-managed lifecycle ensure thread safety when accessed within servlet methods.", "concept_type": "object", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_012", "CHUNK_013"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_003", "CONC_006"]}, {"id": "CONC_006", "title": "HttpServletResponse", "aliases": ["HTTP response"], "keywords": ["response object", "content-type", "output stream"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 3, "description": "HttpServletResponse is a Jakarta Servlet interface representing the server''s response to an HTTP request. It provides methods to set status codes, headers (e.g., Content-Type, Cache-Control), cookies, and to obtain output streams (PrintWriter for text, ServletOutputStream for binary) for writing response bodies. Critical constraints apply: headers and status must be set before acquiring any output stream. Servlets use it to deliver dynamic content (e.g., generated HTML), redirect clients, or send error responses. Proper resource management requires closing PrintWriter or flushing OutputStream before method completion to ensure complete transmission.", "concept_type": "object", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_012", "CHUNK_013"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_003", "CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CONC_007", "title": "doGet() and doPost() Methods", "aliases": ["HTTP verb handlers"], "keywords": ["HTTP method handling", "request dispatching", "form submission"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 2, "description": "doGet() and doPost() are predefined HttpServlet methods designed to handle HTTP GET and POST requests respectively. doGet() is typically used for safe, idempotent operations like retrieving documents or displaying forms; parameters are passed via query string. doPost() handles non-idempotent actions involving sensitive or large payloads (e.g., login, file upload, database updates); parameters are sent in the request body. While semantic distinctions exist, real-world usage often blurs them due to payload size limits of GET. Developers override these methods to implement custom request processing logic, extracting parameters, performing business operations, and populating the response object.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_014", "CHUNK_015"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_003", "CONC_005", "CONC_006"]}, {"id": "CONC_008", "title": "Jakarta EE Web Architecture", "aliases": ["Java EE web architecture"], "keywords": ["Jakarta EE", "MVC", "enterprise web stack", "container model"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 4, "description": "Jakarta EE web architecture defines a layered, containerized model for enterprise web applications. It comprises client browsers, web containers (for servlets/JSP), EJB containers (for business logic), and backend databases. Key components include Application Clients, Web Containers (e.g., GlassFish), EJB Containers, and Jakarta EE APIs (Servlet, JSP, JPA, JTA, JNDI, JMS, JavaMail). The architecture enforces separation of concerns—e.g., MVC—where servlets act as controllers, JSPs as views, and EJBs or POJOs as models. Containers provide cross-cutting services (security, transactions, lifecycle), enabling portable, scalable, and secure enterprise deployments.", "concept_type": "architecture", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_002", "CHUNK_003"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_002", "CONC_004", "CONC_009"]}, {"id": "CONC_009", "title": "Form Data Handling", "aliases": ["client input processing"], "keywords": ["HTML form", "parameter extraction", "checkbox handling", "radio button"], "confidence": 1.0, "difficulty": 2, "description": "Form data handling refers to the process by which servlets extract and process user-submitted data from HTML forms. It involves retrieving single-value parameters (getParameter()) for text inputs and radio buttons, multi-value parameters (getParameterValues()) for checkboxes, and validating presence or emptiness. Common patterns include parsing names, company sizes, IDE preferences, and other structured inputs. This functionality underpins interactive web applications and integrates with business logic, databases, or downstream services. Robust handling requires null checks, encoding awareness (UTF-8), and separation from presentation logic—often delegated to JSPs or templating engines in MVC.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_016", "CHUNK_017", "CHUNK_018"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_007"]}], "relationships": [{"id": "REL_001", "type": "managed_by", "source": "CONC_001", "target": "CONC_002", "evidence": "A web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_002", "type": "part_of", "source": "CONC_001", "target": "CONC_003", "evidence": "Servlets participate directly in the HTTP request-response lifecycle.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_003", "type": "implements", "source": "CONC_002", "target": "CONC_004", "evidence": "Web containers perform URL mapping to locate and dispatch servlets.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_004", "type": "consumes", "source": "CONC_003", "target": "CONC_005", "evidence": "The request-response lifecycle begins with creation of HttpServletRequest.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_005", "type": "produces", "source": "CONC_003", "target": "CONC_006", "evidence": "The lifecycle concludes with population and transmission of HttpServletResponse.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_006", "type": "requires", "source": "CONC_005", "target": "CONC_007", "evidence": "doGet() and doPost() receive HttpServletRequest as their first parameter.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_007", "type": "requires", "source": "CONC_006", "target": "CONC_007", "evidence": "doGet() and doPost() receive HttpServletResponse as their second parameter.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_008", "type": "maps_to", "source": "CONC_004", "target": "CONC_001", "evidence": "URL mapping associates client URLs to servlet classes like MyServlet.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_009", "type": "part_of", "source": "CONC_008", "target": "CONC_002", "evidence": "Web containers are core execution environments in Jakarta EE architecture.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_010", "type": "uses", "source": "CONC_009", "target": "CONC_005", "evidence": "Form data handling relies on HttpServletRequest methods like getParameter().", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}], "quality_metrics": {"total_chunks": 19, "missing_links": [], "coverage_score": 1.0, "total_concepts": 9, "consistency_score": 1.0, "total_relationships": 10}, "processing_notes": {"ambiguous_terms": [], "suggested_review": []}, "document_metadata": {"title": "ITP4511 – Enterprise System Development: Web Application Architecture and Servlet Fundamentals", "language": "English", "main_topic": "Web Application Architecture and Jakarta Servlet Technology", "difficulty_level": "Intermediate", "estimated_reading_time": "25 minutes"}, "concept_chunk_mapping": [{"concept": "Servlet", "context": "Servlet is a technology used to create web application. Servlet is a class that extend the capabilities of the servers...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_003", "positions": [274, 320, 425, 475, 515], "concept_id": "CONC_001", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Servlet", "context": "What Is a Servlet? Servlet is a technology used to create web application...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_004", "positions": [13, 64, 115, 170, 220], "concept_id": "CONC_001", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Web Container", "context": "Tomcat - is just a web container... Servlet is a web component that is deployed on the server...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_003", "positions": [0, 115, 160, 210], "concept_id": "CONC_002", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Web Container", "context": "Web container interacts with Jakarta Servlets. A web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_004", "positions": [142, 210, 275], "concept_id": "CONC_002", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "HTTP Request-Response Lifecycle", "context": "How web server handle a request? When a web server gets a request for a servlet...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_007", "positions": [21, 110, 175, 240], "concept_id": "CONC_003", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "HTTP Request-Response Lifecycle", "context": "How the Container handles a request for a servlet 1. The user clicks a link...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_008", "positions": [31, 220, 350, 480, 610, 740], "concept_id": "CONC_003", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "URL Mapping", "context": "How to find the correct servlet « Use @WebServlet annotation... A can have three names Client-Known URL name...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_010", "positions": [16, 140, 220, 300, 390, 470], "concept_id": "CONC_004", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "HttpServletRequest", "context": "First object type - HttpServletRequest, which contains the client’s request data...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_012", "positions": [115, 225], "concept_id": "CONC_005", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "HttpServletResponse", "context": "Second object type - HttpServletResponse, into which your response to the request is written...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_012", "positions": [255, 375], "concept_id": "CONC_006", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "doGet() and doPost() Methods", "context": "Servlet Demonstration\n\nService()\nHandles the setup and dispatching of doXXX()\ndoGet()\nHandle GET class...", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_014", "positions": [21, 60, 110, 170, 220, 280, 340], "concept_id": "CONC_007", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Form Data Handling", "context": "Examples - Servlet Handles Form Data ° Text box ¢ Radio button ¢ Checkbox", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_016", "positions": [0, 25, 50, 75], "concept_id": "CONC_009", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Form Data Handling", "context": "<%@page contentType=\"text/html\" pageEncoding=\"UTF-8\"%>\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head>\n  <title>Radio Button</title>", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_017", "positions": [0], "concept_id": "CONC_009", "importance": "secondary"}, {"concept": "Form Data Handling", "context": "<%@page contentType=\"text/html\" pageEncoding=\"UTF-8\"%>\n<!DOCTYPE html><html>\n    <head>\n        <title>check box</title>", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_018", "positions": [0], "concept_id": "CONC_009", "importance": "secondary"}]}', '{"total_modules": 5, "total_concepts": 22, "difficulty_score": 9, "total_structures": 18, "total_applications": 16}', '"[{\"id\":\"CHUNK_001\",\"text\":\"ITP4511 – Enterprise System Development\\nWeb Application Architecture ITP4511 - Enterprise System Development\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":0,\"end_pos\":87,\"summary\":\"Course title and module topic identifier.\",\"chunk_type\":\"header\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_002\",\"text\":\"Web Application Arc® Deas ade oe Application Client Container Web Browser Client a Application Client Web Serviet Web Page Container Jakarta EE eos = | “ Enterprise Bean Enterprise Bean EIB GD GD Container Database (((\\nApplication Client Container Application Client Servlet Enterprise Bean D Database Web Browser | zc Web Page B GOO Enterprise Bean D Client Machine Web Container EJB Container\",\"pages\":[2],\"start_pos\":88,\"end_pos\":412,\"summary\":\"Describes layered Jakarta EE architecture with client, web container, EJB container, and database components.\",\"chunk_type\":\"diagram_description\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_008\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_003\",\"text\":\"Tomcat - is just a web container\\nWildFly (Formerly JBoss)\\nBEA''s Weblogic\\nIBM''s WebSphere\\nPayara\\nGlassfish (will be used in this semester)\\n\\nExamples of a container * Tomcat - is just a web container ¢ WildFly (Formerly JBoss) ¢ BEA''s Weblogic IBM''s WebSphere * Payara * Glassfish (will be used in this semester)\\n\\nServlet is a technology\\nused to create web application.\\nServlet is a class that extend the capabilities of the servers and respond to the incoming request. It can respond to any type of requests.\\nServlet is a web component that is deployed on the server to create dynamic web page.\",\"pages\":[3],\"start_pos\":413,\"end_pos\":945,\"summary\":\"Defines servlet as a dynamic web component and lists major web containers including GlassFish as course standard.\",\"chunk_type\":\"definition_and_examples\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_004\",\"text\":\"What Is a Servlet? Servlet is a technology used to create web application. Servlet is a class that extend the capabilities of the servers and respond to the incoming request. It can respond to any type of requests. Servlet is a web component that is deployed on the server to create dynamic web page.\\n\\nWeb container interacts with Jakarta Servlets. \\nA web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets, mapping a URL to a particular servlet and ensuring that the URL requester has the correct access-rights.\",\"pages\":[4],\"start_pos\":946,\"end_pos\":1370,\"summary\":\"Reiterates servlet definition and explicitly states web container responsibilities: lifecycle, URL mapping, and access control.\",\"chunk_type\":\"definition\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_005\",\"text\":\"Web container * Web container interacts with Jakarta Servlets. ¢ A web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets, mapping a URL to a particular servlet and ensuring that the URL requester has the correct access-rights.\",\"pages\":[5],\"start_pos\":1371,\"end_pos\":1575,\"summary\":\"Concise restatement of web container’s core responsibilities toward servlets.\",\"chunk_type\":\"definition\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_006\",\"text\":\"The Container will give you the following Communications support - The container provides an easy way for your servlets to talk to your web server. Lifecycle Management - The container controls the life and death of the serviet, It takes care of loading the classes, instantiating and initializing the servlets, invoking the servlets methods and making servlet instances eligible for garbage collection, it also takes care of resources management. Multithreading Support - The Container automatically creates a new Java thread for every servlet request it receives, there are still issues around synchronization but having the server create and manage the treads for multiple requests still saves you a lot of wor’ Declarative Security - With a Container you get to use an XML deployment descriptor to configure (and modify) security without having to hard-code it into your servlet class code, thus you don''t have to recompile your va source files. JSP Support - The Container takes core of translating JSP into real Java.\",\"pages\":[6],\"start_pos\":1576,\"end_pos\":2458,\"summary\":\"Enumerates key services provided by web containers: communications, lifecycle, threading, declarative security, and JSP support.\",\"chunk_type\":\"feature_list\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_004\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_007\",\"text\":\"How web server handle a request? When a web server gets a request for a servlet, the web server hands the request to the Container in which the servlet is deployed. It''s the Container that gives the servlet the HTTP request and response and it''s the Container that calls the servlet''s methods (doPost() and doGet()).\",\"pages\":[7],\"start_pos\":2459,\"end_pos\":2742,\"summary\":\"Outlines high-level delegation flow: web server → container → servlet invocation.\",\"chunk_type\":\"process_summary\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_003\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_008\",\"text\":\"How the Container handles a request for a servlet 1. The user clicks a link that has a URL to a servlet instead of a static page 2. The container \\\"sees\\\" that the request is for a servlet, so the container creates two objects HttpServiletResponse and HttpServletRequest 3. The container finds the correct servlet based on the URL in the request, creates or allocates a thread for that request and passes the request and response Objects to the servlet thread 4. The container calls the servliet''s service() method, depending on the type of request, the service() methods calls either the doGet() or doPost() method 5. The doGet() method generates the dynamic page and arranges the page into the response object. Remember, the container still has a reference to the response object 6. The thread completes, the container converts the response object into an HTTP response, send it back to the client, then deletes the request and response objects.\",\"pages\":[8],\"start_pos\":2743,\"end_pos\":3517,\"summary\":\"Six-step detailed description of servlet request handling, emphasizing object creation, thread allocation, method dispatch, and response serialization.\",\"chunk_type\":\"stepwise_process\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_003\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\",\"CONC_007\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_009\",\"text\":\"Step 1 ¢ The user clicks a link that has a URL to a servlet instead of a static page Jeez\\n\\nThe container \\\"sees\\\" that the request is for a servlet, so the container creates two objects HttpServietResponse and HttpServietRequest\\n\\nThe container finds the correct servlet based on the URL in the request, creates or allocates a thread for that request and passes the request and response Objects to the servlet thread\\n\\nThe container calls the servlet''s service() method, depending on the type of request, the service() methods calls either the doGet() or doPost() method\\n\\nThe doGet() method generates the dynamic page and puts the page into the response object. Remember, the container still has a reference to the response object\\n\\nStep 6 ° The doGet() method generates the dynamic page and stuffs the page into the response object. Remember, the | ae 0 Container still has a reference to the eis ae arte ie cn\",\"pages\":[9],\"start_pos\":3518,\"end_pos\":4214,\"summary\":\"Annotated step-by-step breakdown of servlet request flow, reinforcing object creation, dispatch, and response binding.\",\"chunk_type\":\"annotated_steps\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_003\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\",\"CONC_007\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_010\",\"text\":\"How to find the correct servlet « Use @WebServiet annotation in Servlet 3.0 in Java EE6. * Prior to Servlet 3.0, you need to register the Serviet using deployment descriptor( web.xm/) by employing <serv/et> or <serviet-mapping> tags.\\n\\nA can have three names Client-Known URL name - The client sees a URL for the servlet but does not know how that servlet name maps to a real directory and file back on the server, the URL is a fake name made up for the clients * Deployer-Known Secret Internal name - The deployer can create a name that''s known only to the deployer and others in the real operational environment, this name again is a fake name made up just for the deployment of the servlet * Actual filename - The developers servlet class has a fully-qualified name that includes both the class name and package name. The class file has a real path and file name, depending on where the package directory structure lives on the server.\",\"pages\":[10],\"start_pos\":4215,\"end_pos\":4952,\"summary\":\"Explains servlet naming layers (client URL, internal name, fully-qualified class) and mapping mechanisms: @WebServlet vs web.xml.\",\"chunk_type\":\"mapping_explanation\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_004\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_011\",\"text\":\"Naming and Mapping Servlets By mapping the name instead of coding in the real file and path name you have the flexibility to move things around without having the maintenance nightmare of tracking down and change client code that refers to the old location of the servlet files, also by mapping the filename you can hide the real directories, thus increasing security.\\nWhen you deploy your servlet into your Web Container, you will tell the Container how to run your servlets and JP. To map URLs to servlets - one to map the client-known public URL name to your own internal name, and the other to map your own internal name to a fully-qualified class name.\",\"pages\":[11],\"start_pos\":4953,\"end_pos\":5487,\"summary\":\"Justifies URL mapping benefits: deployment flexibility, maintainability, and security through abstraction.\",\"chunk_type\":\"rationale\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_004\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_012\",\"text\":\"Each of these methods accepts two input parameters. \\nFirst object type - HttpServletRequest, which contains the client’s request data and methods to retrieve it. \\nSecond object type - HttpServletResponse, into which your response to the request is written. When your servlet finishes executing,  Web container transmits the data contained in this object back to the client.\",\"pages\":[12],\"start_pos\":5488,\"end_pos\":5830,\"summary\":\"Defines HttpServletRequest and HttpServletResponse as mandatory servlet method parameters and explains their roles.\",\"chunk_type\":\"interface_definition\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_003\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_013\",\"text\":\"In line 11 we use a method of the HttpServletResponse object to set the content type of the response that we are going to send. All response headers must be set before a PrintWriter or ServletOutputStream is requested to write body data to the response.\\nIn line 12 we request a PrintWriter object to write text to the response message.\\nIn lines 13 and 14 we use the PrintWriter to write the text of type text/html (as specified through the content-type).\\nThe PrintWriter gets closed in line 15 when we are finished writing to it.\",\"pages\":[13],\"start_pos\":5831,\"end_pos\":6212,\"summary\":\"Details HttpServletResponse usage: header setting order, PrintWriter acquisition, HTML generation, and resource cleanup.\",\"chunk_type\":\"implementation_detail\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_006\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_014\",\"text\":\"Servlet Demonstration\\n\\nService()\\nHandles the setup and dispatching of doXXX()\\ndoGet()\\nHandle GET class\\nExample: a document or an html page \\nAdditional information (or, a query string) can be appended to the GET method to refine the request \\ndoPost()\\nHandle POST request\\nExample: a credit card number, new data to be stored \\nSometimes megabytes of information can be sent \\nOther predefined methods: doHead(), doTrace(), doOptions()\",\"pages\":[14],\"start_pos\":6213,\"end_pos\":6611,\"summary\":\"Documents HttpServlet’s standard methods, distinguishing doGet() (safe, idempotent) and doPost() (state-changing, large payload).\",\"chunk_type\":\"method_reference\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_007\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_015\",\"text\":\"Things You Do in doGet() & doPost() Extract client-sent information (HTTP parameter) from HTTP request ° Set (Save) and get (read) attributes to/from Scope objects ° Perform some business logic or access database * Optionally forward the request to other Web components (Servlet or JSP) * Populate HTTP response message and send it to client ° In practice, the distinction in the use of GET and POST has been blurred, since complicated requests may need to send more data than a GET can support so that POST is used instead\",\"pages\":[15],\"start_pos\":6612,\"end_pos\":7029,\"summary\":\"Lists common tasks inside doGet()/doPost(): parameter extraction, scope manipulation, business logic, forwarding, and response population.\",\"chunk_type\":\"functional_specification\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_007\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_016\",\"text\":\"Examples - Servlet Handles Form Data ° Text box ¢ Radio button ¢ Checkbox\\n\\nText Box “T Et eer ees ra t Introduction é By.Customize Links. [) Suggested Sites Web Slice Gallery € > G (© tocathost3080/3_ SERVLET_DEMO/texthtm! DQ % & 6 a | Other bookmarks\\n€ > S [O localhost8080/3_SERVLET_OEMO/texthtml O) D) SuggestedStes D) Web Stice Gattery $C Otherbootmnarts, Pate ean |]\\n<%@page contentType=\\\"text/html\\\" pageEncoding=\\\"UTF-8\\\"%>\\n<!DOCTYPE html>\\n<html>\\n    <head>\\n        <title>Introduction</title>\\n    </head>\\n    <body>\\n        <form method=\\\"get\\\" action=\\\"hello\\\">\\n            please enter your name:\\n            <input type=text name=\\\"name\\\">\\n            <p><input type=\\\"submit\\\">\\n        </form>\\n    </body>\\n</html>\",\"pages\":[16],\"start_pos\":7030,\"end_pos\":7628,\"summary\":\"Introduces form data types and provides HTML example for text input with GET submission.\",\"chunk_type\":\"example_form\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_009\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_017\",\"text\":\"<%@page contentType=\\\"text/html\\\" pageEncoding=\\\"UTF-8\\\"%>\\n<!DOCTYPE html>\\n<html>\\n<head>\\n  <title>Radio Button</title>\\n</head>\\n<body>\\n    <form  method=\\\"get\\\"  action=\\\"radio\\\" >   \\n        <br>How many employees in your company?<br>\\n        <br>1-100<input type=\\\"radio\\\" name=\\\"employee\\\" value=\\\"1-100\\\" />\\n        <br>100-200<input type=\\\"radio\\\" name=\\\"employee\\\" value=\\\"100-200\\\" />\\n        <br>200-300<input type=\\\"radio\\\" name=\\\"employee\\\" value=\\\"200-300\\\"/>\\n        <br>300-400<input type=\\\"radio\\\" name=\\\"employee\\\" value=\\\"300-400\\\"/>\\n        <br>500-more<input type=\\\"radio\\\" name=\\\"employee\\\" value=\\\"500-more\\\"/>\\n     <br/><input type=\\\"submit\\\">\\n  </form>\\n</body>\\n</html>\",\"pages\":[17],\"start_pos\":7629,\"end_pos\":8049,\"summary\":\"HTML form example demonstrating radio button usage with shared ''name'' attribute.\",\"chunk_type\":\"example_form\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_009\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_018\",\"text\":\"<%@page contentType=\\\"text/html\\\" pageEncoding=\\\"UTF-8\\\"%>\\n<!DOCTYPE html><html>\\n    <head>\\n        <title>check box</title>\\n    </head>\\n    <body>\\n        <form method=get action=\\\"/lab3/checkbox\\\">\\n            <br/>what ides do you use?<br>\\n            <br/>Netbean <input type=\\\"checkbox\\\" name=\\\"ide\\\" value=\\\"netbean\\\" >\\n            <br/>Jdeveloper <input type=\\\"checkbox\\\" name=\\\"ide\\\" value=\\\"jdeveloper\\\"/>\\n            <br/>Eclipse?<input type=\\\"checkbox\\\" name=\\\"ide\\\"  value=\\\"eclipse\\\" />\\n            <p><input type=\\\"submit\\\">\\n        </form>\\n    </body>\\n</html>\",\"pages\":[18],\"start_pos\":8050,\"end_pos\":8423,\"summary\":\"HTML form example illustrating checkbox group with same ''name'' and distinct ''value'' attributes.\",\"chunk_type\":\"example_form\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_009\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"CONC_001\",\"title\":\"Servlet\",\"aliases\":[\"HTTP servlet\",\"Java servlet\"],\"keywords\":[\"Jakarta Servlet\",\"HTTP handler\",\"server-side Java\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A servlet is a Java class that extends server capabilities to handle client requests dynamically. It is a web component deployed in a web container, conforming to the Jakarta Servlet specification. Servlets respond to HTTP requests (e.g., GET, POST) by implementing methods like doGet() or doPost(), and they generate dynamic content—typically HTML—by writing to an HttpServletResponse object. Servlets are managed entirely by the container, which handles lifecycle, threading, security, and request-response binding. They require no direct socket programming and abstract low-level network concerns, enabling developers to focus on business logic.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_003\",\"CHUNK_004\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_007\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_002\",\"title\":\"Web Container\",\"aliases\":[\"Servlet container\"],\"keywords\":[\"servlet container\",\"Jakarta EE container\",\"runtime environment\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A web container is a runtime environment that manages Jakarta servlets and JSPs within a Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE) application server. It provides essential services including servlet lifecycle management (loading, instantiation, initialization, garbage collection), URL-to-servlet mapping, multithreaded request handling, declarative security via deployment descriptors or annotations, JSP translation, and communication support between servlets and the underlying web server. Examples include Tomcat, GlassFish, WildFly, WebLogic, and WebSphere. The container acts as an intermediary between the HTTP server and servlet code, invoking service(), doGet(), or doPost() based on request type.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_003\",\"CHUNK_005\",\"CHUNK_006\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_004\",\"CONC_008\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_003\",\"title\":\"HTTP Request-Response Lifecycle\",\"aliases\":[\"servlet request flow\",\"HTTP handling sequence\"],\"keywords\":[\"request dispatch\",\"thread per request\",\"service lifecycle\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":4,\"description\":\"The HTTP request-response lifecycle describes the end-to-end flow from client browser submission to server response delivery. It begins when a user clicks a link targeting a servlet URL; the web server delegates the request to the web container. The container creates HttpServletRequest and HttpServletResponse objects, locates the mapped servlet, allocates a thread, invokes service(), which dispatches to doGet() or doPost() based on method. The servlet processes input, executes business logic, populates the response, and returns control. Finally, the container serializes the response into HTTP format and transmits it back to the client. Thread cleanup and object disposal follow completion.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_007\",\"CHUNK_008\",\"CHUNK_009\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_006\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_004\",\"title\":\"URL Mapping\",\"aliases\":[\"servlet registration\",\"endpoint binding\"],\"keywords\":[\"@WebServlet\",\"web.xml\",\"servlet mapping\",\"deployment descriptor\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"URL mapping is the mechanism that binds client-visible URLs to internal servlet names and ultimately to fully qualified Java class names. It decouples public endpoint naming from physical deployment, enabling flexibility and security. Two layers exist: (1) client-known URL name (e.g., ''/firstServlet'') mapped to a deployer-known internal name (e.g., ''MyServlet''), and (2) internal name mapped to a class (e.g., ''ict.servlet.MyServlet''). Mapping is achieved either declaratively via web.xml (<servlet> and <servlet-mapping>) or programmatically using @WebServlet annotation (introduced in Servlet 3.0). This abstraction prevents hardcoding paths and supports refactoring without breaking client integrations.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_010\",\"CHUNK_011\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_005\",\"title\":\"HttpServletRequest\",\"aliases\":[\"HTTP request\"],\"keywords\":[\"request object\",\"form data extraction\",\"HTTP parameter\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"HttpServletRequest is a Jakarta Servlet interface representing an HTTP request received by a servlet. It encapsulates client metadata—including HTTP method, headers, query parameters, form data, cookies, session information, and input streams—and provides methods to extract this data (e.g., getParameter(), getParameterValues(), getHeader(), getSession()). It serves as the primary conduit for retrieving user-submitted information such as form fields (text boxes, radio buttons, checkboxes) and enables stateful interaction through scoped attributes and session tracking. Its immutability and container-managed lifecycle ensure thread safety when accessed within servlet methods.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_012\",\"CHUNK_013\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_006\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_006\",\"title\":\"HttpServletResponse\",\"aliases\":[\"HTTP response\"],\"keywords\":[\"response object\",\"content-type\",\"output stream\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"HttpServletResponse is a Jakarta Servlet interface representing the server''s response to an HTTP request. It provides methods to set status codes, headers (e.g., Content-Type, Cache-Control), cookies, and to obtain output streams (PrintWriter for text, ServletOutputStream for binary) for writing response bodies. Critical constraints apply: headers and status must be set before acquiring any output stream. Servlets use it to deliver dynamic content (e.g., generated HTML), redirect clients, or send error responses. Proper resource management requires closing PrintWriter or flushing OutputStream before method completion to ensure complete transmission.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_012\",\"CHUNK_013\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_007\",\"title\":\"doGet() and doPost() Methods\",\"aliases\":[\"HTTP verb handlers\"],\"keywords\":[\"HTTP method handling\",\"request dispatching\",\"form submission\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"doGet() and doPost() are predefined HttpServlet methods designed to handle HTTP GET and POST requests respectively. doGet() is typically used for safe, idempotent operations like retrieving documents or displaying forms; parameters are passed via query string. doPost() handles non-idempotent actions involving sensitive or large payloads (e.g., login, file upload, database updates); parameters are sent in the request body. While semantic distinctions exist, real-world usage often blurs them due to payload size limits of GET. Developers override these methods to implement custom request processing logic, extracting parameters, performing business operations, and populating the response object.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_014\",\"CHUNK_015\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_008\",\"title\":\"Jakarta EE Web Architecture\",\"aliases\":[\"Java EE web architecture\"],\"keywords\":[\"Jakarta EE\",\"MVC\",\"enterprise web stack\",\"container model\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":4,\"description\":\"Jakarta EE web architecture defines a layered, containerized model for enterprise web applications. It comprises client browsers, web containers (for servlets/JSP), EJB containers (for business logic), and backend databases. Key components include Application Clients, Web Containers (e.g., GlassFish), EJB Containers, and Jakarta EE APIs (Servlet, JSP, JPA, JTA, JNDI, JMS, JavaMail). The architecture enforces separation of concerns—e.g., MVC—where servlets act as controllers, JSPs as views, and EJBs or POJOs as models. Containers provide cross-cutting services (security, transactions, lifecycle), enabling portable, scalable, and secure enterprise deployments.\",\"concept_type\":\"architecture\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_002\",\"CHUNK_003\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_004\",\"CONC_009\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_009\",\"title\":\"Form Data Handling\",\"aliases\":[\"client input processing\"],\"keywords\":[\"HTML form\",\"parameter extraction\",\"checkbox handling\",\"radio button\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"Form data handling refers to the process by which servlets extract and process user-submitted data from HTML forms. It involves retrieving single-value parameters (getParameter()) for text inputs and radio buttons, multi-value parameters (getParameterValues()) for checkboxes, and validating presence or emptiness. Common patterns include parsing names, company sizes, IDE preferences, and other structured inputs. This functionality underpins interactive web applications and integrates with business logic, databases, or downstream services. Robust handling requires null checks, encoding awareness (UTF-8), and separation from presentation logic—often delegated to JSPs or templating engines in MVC.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_016\",\"CHUNK_017\",\"CHUNK_018\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_007\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"REL_001\",\"type\":\"managed_by\",\"source\":\"CONC_001\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"A web container is responsible for managing the lifecycle of servlets.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_002\",\"type\":\"part_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_001\",\"target\":\"CONC_003\",\"evidence\":\"Servlets participate directly in the HTTP request-response lifecycle.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_003\",\"type\":\"implements\",\"source\":\"CONC_002\",\"target\":\"CONC_004\",\"evidence\":\"Web containers perform URL mapping to locate and dispatch servlets.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_004\",\"type\":\"consumes\",\"source\":\"CONC_003\",\"target\":\"CONC_005\",\"evidence\":\"The request-response lifecycle begins with creation of HttpServletRequest.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_005\",\"type\":\"produces\",\"source\":\"CONC_003\",\"target\":\"CONC_006\",\"evidence\":\"The lifecycle concludes with population and transmission of HttpServletResponse.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_006\",\"type\":\"requires\",\"source\":\"CONC_005\",\"target\":\"CONC_007\",\"evidence\":\"doGet() and doPost() receive HttpServletRequest as their first parameter.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_007\",\"type\":\"requires\",\"source\":\"CONC_006\",\"target\":\"CONC_007\",\"evidence\":\"doGet() and doPost() receive HttpServletResponse as their second parameter.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_008\",\"type\":\"maps_to\",\"source\":\"CONC_004\",\"target\":\"CONC_001\",\"evidence\":\"URL mapping associates client URLs to servlet classes like MyServlet.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_009\",\"type\":\"part_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_008\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"Web containers are core execution environments in Jakarta EE architecture.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_010\",\"type\":\"uses\",\"source\":\"CONC_009\",\"target\":\"CONC_005\",\"evidence\":\"Form data handling relies on HttpServletRequest methods like getParameter().\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false}]"', '2026-03-25 07:30:12.58905', '2026-03-25 07:30:12.58905', NULL, '[{"id": "module_1", "name": "Web Application Architecture & Containers", "topic_count": 12}, {"id": "module_2", "name": "Servlet Fundamentals & Lifecycle", "topic_count": 14}, {"id": "module_3", "name": "Servlet Implementation & Mapping", "topic_count": 10}, {"id": "module_4", "name": "Handling HTTP Requests & Form Data", "topic_count": 15}, {"id": "module_5", "name": "Servlet Advantages & Use Cases", "topic_count": 5}]', NULL, 'ITP4511 – Enterprise System Development

