[Full Slide OCR]:
A can have three names Client-Known URL name - The client sees a URL for the servlet but does not know how that servlet name maps to a real directory and file back on the server, the URL is a fake name made up for the clients * Deployer-Known Secret Internal name - The deployer can create a name that''s known only to the deployer and others in the real operational environment, this name again is a fake name made up just for the deployment of the servlet * Actual filename - The developers servlet class has a fully-qualified name that includes both the class name and package name. The class file has a real path and file name, depending on where the package directory structure lives on the server.

By mapping the name instead of coding in the real file and path name you have the flexibility to move things around without having the maintenance nightmare of tracking down and change client code that refers to the old location of the servlet files, also by mapping the filename you can hide the real directories, thus increasing security.
When you deploy your servlet into your Web Container, you will  tell the Container how to run your servlets and JP. 
To map URLs to servlets - one to map the client-known public URL name to your own internal name, and the other to map your own internal name to a fully-qualified class name.

