Each of these methods accepts two input parameters. 
First object type - HttpServletRequest, which contains the client’s request data and methods to retrieve it. 
Second object type - HttpServletResponse, into which your response to the request is written.  When your servlet finishes executing,  Web container transmits the data contained in this object back to the client.

[Full Slide OCR]:
Input parameters Each of these methods accepts two input parameters. First object type - HttpServletRequest, which contains the client’s request data and methods to retrieve it. Second object type - HttpServietResponse, into which your response to the request is written. When your servlet finishes executing, Web container transmits the data contained in this object back to the client.

Override the service() method. This causes your servlet to respond to all requests in the same way. This is usually sufficient and is the path most Application developers take.
Override one or more of the doXXX() methods. This enables you to respond to different types of requests in different ways. But your servlet will return an error message if you receive a request type that you do not support.

