Servlets is to service clients.
Its job is to take a client''s request and send back a response. The request carries crucial data, and your servlet code has to know how to find it and how to use it. The response carries the info the browser needs to render a page and your servlet code has to know how to send it, it can decide to send it to something else (another page, servlet, JSP) instead.

[Full Slide OCR]:
The responsibility of the Servlet Servlets is to service clients. Its job is to take a client''s request and send back a response. The request carries crucial data, and your code has to know how to find it and how to use it. The response carries the info the browser needs to render a page and your servlet code has to know how to send it, it can decide to send it to something else (another page, servlet, JSP) instead.

The servlet creates the request and response objects, creates or allocates a new thread for the servlet and calls the servlets service() method, passing the request and response references as arguments.

[Full Slide OCR]:
The servlet creates the request and response objects, creates or allocates a new thread for the servlet and calls the servlets service() method, passing the request and response references as arguments.

The servlet has only one main state initialized
If it isn''t initialized then it''s either being initialized (running its constructor or init() method) or being destroyed (running its destroy() method) or it simply does not exist.
NO main class found.
Servlet is maintained by the container

[Full Slide OCR]:
Life of Servlet * The servlet has only one main state initialized * If itisn''t initialized then it’s either being initialized (running its constructor or init() method) or being destroyed (running its destroy() method) or it simply does not exist. NO main class found. Servlet is maintained by the container

First the servlet classes are loaded 
Then the servlet instantiates (constructor runs)
init() method is called only once
service() method is called (this is were the servlet spends most of its life, handing users requests)
finally the destroy() method is called (cleans up and made ready for garbage collection)

[Full Slide OCR]:
Servlets Life Cycle * First the servlet classes are loaded * Then the servlet instantiates (constructor runs) * jnit() method is called only once * service() method is called (this is were the servlet spends most of its life, handing users requests) ° finally the destroy() method is called (cleans up and made ready for garbage collection)

Instantiation:  default constructor()
This happens once in the servlet’s lifetime
Initialization - the init() method 
To create an instance of a Servlet class Done once 
Overriding the init() method is your opportunity to perform one time initialization of data structures, database connections, class variables, and etc. 
Service - the service() method 
Calls the appropriate doXXX() method.
Each request is handled concurrently by threads
Destruction - the destroy() method 
To destroy the Serlvet and tidy up the resources Done once

[Full Slide OCR]:
The Servlet Life Cycle Handled by the Container ¢ Instantiation: default constructor() * This happens once in the servlet’s lifetime * Initialization - the init() method * To create an instance of a Servlet class Done once * Overriding the init() method is your opportunity to perform one time initialization of data structures, database connections, class variables, and etc. ° Service - the service() method * Calls the appropriate doXXX() method. * Each request is handled concurrently by threads * Destruction - the destroy() method * To destroy the Serlvet and tidy up the resources Done once

After a servlet is loaded into the JVM, the same instance of the servlet is used to respond to all client requests for that servlet, until either the servlet is modified or Application Server restarts. 
When either of those events happens, Web container calls the servlet’s destroy() method before unloading it from the JVM.

[Full Slide OCR]:
