ectricity is supplied to our homes through two wires: the live wire and the neutral wire. 3 We should avoid connecting too many appliances to a mains socket, because they will draw a large current and overloading occurs. 4 A short circuit provides a branch with a very low resistance for current to flow. It may be caused by a loose wire, or even dust and moisture on the circuit. This must be avoided. 5 The earth wire connects the metal case of an electrical appliance to the ground. It protects us from an electric shock.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":0,\"end_pos\":452,\"summary\":\"Defines core household electricity concepts: mains voltage, live/neutral/earth wires, overloading, short circuit, and electric shock.\",\"chunk_type\":\"fill_in_the_blanks\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_004\",\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\",\"CONC_007\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_002\",\"text\":\"Label different parts of the mains socket and the three-pin plug shown below with the words given. blue brown greenand yellow connecting wire fuse earthhole earth pin earth wire livehole livepin live wire neutralhole neutral pin neutral wire Mains socket Three-pin plug (front) 1] earth hole (1) 4§] earth pin (1) 28 live hole (1) 5 Wiring of three-pin plug (back) 78 earth wire (i) Colour: 8 green and yellow (1) 98 neutral wire (1) Colour: 10 8 blue (1)\",\"pages\":[2],\"start_pos\":453,\"end_pos\":910,\"summary\":\"Identifies physical components and color coding of three-pin plugs and sockets, emphasizing safety wiring conventions.\",\"chunk_type\":\"labelling\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_004\",\"CONC_009\",\"CONC_014\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_003\",\"text\":\"2 Sockets at home are connected in parallel to the mains supply. 3 When more parallel branches are added to a circuit, the current in the main loop decreases. 4 The rating of a fuse shows the average current which can flow through it without breaking the circuit.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":911,\"end_pos\":1120,\"summary\":\"Tests understanding of parallel circuit behavior and fuse functionality, correcting misconceptions about current distribution.\",\"chunk_type\":\"true_or_false\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_015\",\"CONC_009\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_016\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_004\",\"text\":\"3 Which of the following devices has the same function as the fuse? A Ammeter B Rheostat C Switch D Circuit breaker 5 Which of the following statements about the earth wire is / are correct? (1) The earth wire connects the metal case of the appliance to the ground. (2) The current flows to the ground through the earth wire when the live wire touches the metal case accidentally. (3) The earth wire blows when a fault occurs.\",\"pages\":[3],\"start_pos\":1121,\"end_pos\":1412,\"summary\":\"Assesses functional equivalence of protective devices and validates earth wire properties including fault-path role.\",\"chunk_type\":\"multiple_choice\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_008\",\"CONC_004\",\"CONC_009\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_005\",\"text\":\"1 We use electrical power to tell how fast an appliance converts electrical energy to other forms. 2 The unit of power is the watt (W). A larger unit of power is the kilowatt (kW). 3 The power rating is the power of the appliance when it is working at the indicated voltage rating. 4 Efficiency = useful power output / power input x 100% 5 Many appliances have an energy label to show how efficient they are. 6 A joulemeter or a kilowatt-hour meter can be used to measure the electrical energy consumed by appliances.\",\"pages\":[4],\"start_pos\":1413,\"end_pos\":1825,\"summary\":\"Introduces power fundamentals, units, efficiency calculation, labeling, and energy measurement tools.\",\"chunk_type\":\"fill_in_the_blanks\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\",\"CONC_011\",\"CONC_012\",\"CONC_013\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_006\",\"text\":\"a Calculate the power of the bulb. (2 marks) Power = energy / time = 1200 / 60 = 20 W b Find the useful power output of the bulb. Light energy = 1200 − 300 = 900 J → Useful power output = 900 / 60 = 15 W c Calculate the efficiency of the bulb. Efficiency = 15/20 × 100% = 75%\",\"pages\":[5],\"start_pos\":1826,\"end_pos\":2120,\"summary\":\"Applies power and efficiency formulas to real-world LED lamp data, demonstrating quantitative reasoning.\",\"chunk_type\":\"structured_question\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\",\"CONC_012\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_013\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_007\",\"text\":\"10 Electrical appliances are connected in parallel to the mains socket. Which of the following are the advantages? (1) All appliances can work at the same voltage. (2) Each appliance can be switched on and off independently. (3) The power consumed by each appliance is the same.\",\"pages\":[6],\"start_pos\":2121,\"end_pos\":2345,\"summary\":\"Evaluates understanding of practical benefits of parallel domestic wiring configurations.\",\"chunk_type\":\"multiple_choice\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_015\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_008\",\"text\":\"A student connects a thick nichrome wire, an ammeter and a bulb in series with a battery. ... e The wire is then connected back to the circuit. What will happen to the reading of the ammeter? The ammeter reading decreases. The wire becomes longer and thinner. Hence its resistance increases. As the resistance in the circuit increases, the current decreases.\",\"pages\":[9],\"start_pos\":2346,\"end_pos\":2690,\"summary\":\"Illustrates series circuit behavior and resistance dependence on geometry, linking physical changes to electrical outcomes.\",\"chunk_type\":\"high_order_question\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_016\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_009\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"CONC_001\",\"title\":\"Mains voltage\",\"aliases\":[\"supply voltage\",\"domestic voltage\"],\"keywords\":[\"220 V\",\"AC supply\",\"Hong Kong standard\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"The standard electrical potential difference supplied to residential buildings. In Hong Kong, it is 220 V alternating current (AC), providing the baseline energy source for all household appliances. This voltage is maintained across the live and neutral wires and must be strictly regulated to ensure safe and consistent operation of devices rated for this supply.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_002\",\"title\":\"Live wire\",\"aliases\":[\"phase wire\",\"hot wire\"],\"keywords\":[\"brown wire\",\"high potential\",\"fused conductor\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"A current-carrying conductor in a mains circuit that maintains a high potential (220 V relative to earth) and delivers electrical energy from the supply. It is typically color-coded brown in three-pin plug systems and must always be fused on the live side for safety. Contact with the live wire while grounded poses severe risk of electric shock.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_007\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_003\",\"title\":\"Neutral wire\",\"aliases\":[\"return wire\"],\"keywords\":[\"blue wire\",\"return path\",\"near-zero potential\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"A return path conductor in a mains circuit that completes the electrical loop by carrying current back to the supply transformer. It is maintained near earth potential (0 V) under normal conditions and is color-coded blue. While less hazardous than the live wire, it can become energized during faults and must never be assumed safe without verification.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_007\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_004\",\"title\":\"Earth wire\",\"aliases\":[\"ground wire\",\"protective earth\"],\"keywords\":[\"green-and-yellow\",\"safety ground\",\"fault path\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A safety conductor that connects the metal casing of an appliance directly to the ground (earth). Its purpose is to provide a low-resistance path for fault current to flow safely away if the live wire contacts the casing, thereby preventing electric shock by triggering the circuit breaker or fuse. It is color-coded green-and-yellow and is not intended to carry current under normal operation.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\",\"CHUNK_004\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_007\",\"CONC_008\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_005\",\"title\":\"Overloading\",\"aliases\":[\"circuit overload\"],\"keywords\":[\"excessive current\",\"thermal hazard\",\"circuit capacity\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A hazardous condition that occurs when too many appliances draw excessive current through a single circuit or socket, exceeding its designed capacity. This causes overheating of wires, insulation damage, and fire risk. It is prevented by using appropriately rated fuses or circuit breakers and distributing loads across multiple circuits.\",\"concept_type\":\"phenomenon\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_008\",\"CONC_012\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_006\",\"title\":\"Short circuit\",\"aliases\":[\"short\"],\"keywords\":[\"low resistance path\",\"fault current\",\"live-neutral contact\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"An abnormal low-resistance connection between two points of different potential in a circuit—typically between live and neutral or live and earth. It bypasses the normal load, causing dangerously high current flow, rapid heating, and potential fire or equipment damage. Common causes include damaged insulation, loose wires, or moisture ingress.\",\"concept_type\":\"phenomenon\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_008\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_007\",\"title\":\"Electric shock\",\"aliases\":[\"shock hazard\"],\"keywords\":[\"current through body\",\"physiological hazard\",\"safety failure\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"Physiological injury caused by electric current passing through the human body. Severity depends on current magnitude, pathway, duration, and frequency. In household contexts, it most commonly results from contact with a live conductor while grounded or from faulty earthing. Prevention relies on proper insulation, earthing, double insulation, and protective devices like RCDs or circuit breakers.\",\"concept_type\":\"phenomenon\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_004\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_008\",\"title\":\"Circuit breaker\",\"aliases\":[\"MCB\",\"breaker\"],\"keywords\":[\"resettable protection\",\"overcurrent detection\",\"thermal-magnetic\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"An automatically operated electrical switch designed to protect a circuit from damage due to overcurrent or short circuit. Unlike a fuse, it is resettable after tripping. It detects excess current via thermal or magnetic mechanisms and interrupts the live conductor. In modern installations, it replaces fuses as the primary overcurrent protection device.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\",\"CHUNK_004\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_006\",\"CONC_012\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_009\",\"title\":\"Fuse\",\"aliases\":[\"cartridge fuse\"],\"keywords\":[\"sacrificial device\",\"melting element\",\"ampere rating\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"A sacrificial overcurrent protection device containing a metal wire or strip that melts when excessive current flows, thereby breaking the circuit. Rated in amperes (e.g., 5 A, 13 A), it must be placed in series on the live wire. Its rating should match the cable''s current-carrying capacity—not the appliance''s demand—to prevent fire hazards.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_002\",\"CHUNK_004\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_008\",\"CONC_012\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_010\",\"title\":\"Electrical power\",\"aliases\":[\"power consumption\",\"instantaneous power\"],\"keywords\":[\"watt\",\"energy transfer rate\",\"P = VI\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"The rate at which electrical energy is transferred by an electric circuit, measured in watts (W). For resistive loads, power equals voltage multiplied by current (P = VI). It quantifies how fast an appliance converts electrical energy into other forms such as heat, light, or motion. Larger units include kilowatt (kW) for appliances and megawatt (MW) for grid-scale generation.\",\"concept_type\":\"theory\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_005\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_011\",\"CONC_013\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_011\",\"title\":\"Power rating\",\"aliases\":[\"rated power\"],\"keywords\":[\"nameplate value\",\"rated voltage\",\"design load\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"The nominal electrical power an appliance is designed to consume when operating at its specified voltage (e.g., 220 V). It appears on nameplates and determines appropriate fuse sizing, wiring gauge, and circuit loading. Exceeding this rating may cause overheating or failure; operating below it typically reduces performance but not safety.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_005\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\",\"CONC_012\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_012\",\"title\":\"Energy efficiency\",\"aliases\":[\"efficiency\",\"energy conversion ratio\"],\"keywords\":[\"efficiency formula\",\"useful output\",\"energy label\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"The ratio of useful energy output to total energy input, expressed as a percentage. For electrical appliances, it measures how effectively they convert electricity into desired outputs (e.g., light, heat, motion) versus waste (e.g., heat loss in motors, standby consumption). Higher efficiency reduces electricity bills and environmental impact, and is indicated by energy labels (e.g., Grade 1 in Hong Kong).\",\"concept_type\":\"theory\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_005\",\"CHUNK_006\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\",\"CONC_013\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_013\",\"title\":\"Kilowatt-hour meter\",\"aliases\":[\"electricity meter\",\"utility meter\"],\"keywords\":[\"utility meter\",\"energy billing\",\"kW·h\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"A measuring instrument that records the cumulative electrical energy consumed over time, expressed in kilowatt-hours (kW·h). One kW·h equals 3.6 million joules—the energy used by a 1-kW device operating for one hour. Utilities use it for billing; it differs from a wattmeter, which measures instantaneous power.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_005\",\"CHUNK_007\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_010\",\"CONC_012\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_014\",\"title\":\"Three-pin plug\",\"aliases\":[\"BS 1363 plug\"],\"keywords\":[\"live-neutral-earth\",\"polarized plug\",\"HK standard\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"A standardized electrical connector used in Hong Kong and other regions with 220–240 V AC supply. It contains three pins: live (brown wire), neutral (blue wire), and earth (green-and-yellow wire), each corresponding to dedicated holes in the socket. Designed for safety, polarity, and grounding, it ensures correct connection of appliances with exposed metal parts.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_002\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_004\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_015\",\"title\":\"Parallel circuit\",\"aliases\":[\"shunt circuit\"],\"keywords\":[\"independent branches\",\"voltage uniformity\",\"additive current\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"An electrical configuration where components are connected across common nodes, providing multiple independent paths for current flow. In household wiring, sockets and appliances are connected in parallel so that each receives full mains voltage (220 V), operates independently, and does not affect others if switched off or faulty. Total current equals sum of branch currents.\",\"concept_type\":\"architecture\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_003\",\"CHUNK_007\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\",\"CONC_016\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_016\",\"title\":\"Series circuit\",\"aliases\":[\"daisy-chain\"],\"keywords\":[\"single path\",\"current uniformity\",\"voltage division\"],\"confidence\":1,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"An electrical configuration where components are connected end-to-end in a single path, so the same current flows through all elements. Voltage is divided among components proportionally to their resistance. Not used for household power distribution due to dependency—if one device fails, the entire circuit opens—but common in simple experiments and some control circuits.\",\"concept_type\":\"architecture\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_008\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_015\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"REL_001\",\"type\":\"produces\",\"source\":\"CONC_001\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"Mains voltage is present on the live wire.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_002\",\"type\":\"produces\",\"source\":\"CONC_001\",\"target\":\"CONC_003\",\"evidence\":\"Mains voltage is referenced between live and neutral.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_003\",\"type\":\"requires\",\"source\":\"CONC_002\",\"target\":\"CONC_004\",\"evidence\":\"Earth wire provides safety against live-wire faults.\",\"strength\":0.95,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_004\",\"type\":\"managed_by\",\"source\":\"CONC_005\",\"target\":\"CONC_009\",\"evidence\":\"Fuses protect circuits from overloading.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_005\",\"type\":\"managed_by\",\"source\":\"CONC_006\",\"target\":\"CONC_009\",\"evidence\":\"Fuses interrupt short-circuit currents.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_006\",\"type\":\"prevented_by\",\"source\":\"CONC_007\",\"target\":\"CONC_004\",\"evidence\":\"Earth wire prevents electric shock during casing faults.\",\"strength\":0.98,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_007\",\"type\":\"similar_to\",\"source\":\"CONC_008\",\"target\":\"CONC_009\",\"evidence\":\"Both provide overcurrent protection; circuit breaker is resettable, fuse is sacrificial.\",\"strength\":0.9,\"bidirectional\":true},{\"id\":\"REL_008\",\"type\":\"example_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_010\",\"target\":\"CONC_011\",\"evidence\":\"Power rating is a specific instance of electrical power specification.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_009\",\"type\":\"requires\",\"source\":\"CONC_012\",\"target\":\"CONC_010\",\"evidence\":\"Efficiency calculation requires power input and output values.\",\"strength\":0.95,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_010\",\"type\":\"measures\",\"source\":\"CONC_013\",\"target\":\"CONC_012\",\"evidence\":\"Kilowatt-hour meter data enables annual efficiency assessment.\",\"strength\":0.9,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_011\",\"type\":\"part_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_014\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"Live pin is a physical component of the three-pin plug.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_012\",\"type\":\"part_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_014\",\"target\":\"CONC_003\",\"evidence\":\"Neutral pin is a physical component of the three-pin plug.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_013\",\"type\":\"part_of\",\"source\":\"CONC_014\",\"target\":\"CONC_004\",\"evidence\":\"Earth pin is a physical component of the three-pin plug.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_014\",\"type\":\"located_in\",\"source\":\"CONC_015\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"Household sockets connect in parallel to the live supply.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_015\",\"type\":\"located_in\",\"source\":\"CONC_015\",\"target\":\"CONC_003\",\"evidence\":\"Household sockets connect in parallel to the neutral supply.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false}]"', '2026-03-26 08:02:52.739949', '2026-03-26 08:02:52.739949', NULL, '[{"id": "module_1", "name": "Household Electricity and Safety", "topic_count": 18}, {"id": "module_2", "name": "Electrical Power and Efficiency", "topic_count": 15}, {"id": "module_3", "name": "Circuit Components and Symbols", "topic_count": 12}, {"id": "module_4", "name": "Circuit Analysis and Measurements", "topic_count": 20}, {"id": "module_5", "name": "Energy Consumption and Cost", "topic_count": 10}, {"id": "module_6", "name": "Practical Investigations and Applications", "topic_count": 10}]', NULL, '
