Introduction to Spring Boot

What is Spring Boot?
•
Spring Boot is a framework that makes it easy to create
•
Spring-based applications:
•
Stand-alone & production-grade Spring applications
•
Embedded Tomcat, Jetty or Undertow server

Starter dependencies  Spring Boot
•
Starter dependencies > simplify build configuration
•
Automatic configuration of Spring and 3d party libraries
•
Production-ready features: metrics, health checks ＆
externalized configuration
•
No code generation. No XML configuration

Features of Spring Boot
•
Create stand-alone Spring applications with embedded server
•
(Tomcat, Jetty, or Undertow) 
•
No need to deploy WAR files
•
Use Starter Dependencies to simplify dependency configuration
•
Automatic configuration of Spring and 3ra party libraries
•
Provide production-ready features: metrics, health checks,
externalized configuration
•
No code generation. No XML configuration required
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pER-N4esW58&list=TLPQMjExMjIwMjHtUYnCz_3UaQ&index=13

What is Spring Boot exactly about?
•
a project platform
•
is a way that helps developers get started with Spring framework 
with minimum effort, easier and more convenient
•
makes it easy to create stand-alone, production-grade
•
Spring-based apps
•
Developers use Spring Boot to save time and increase 
productivity

Role of Spring Boot in 
Microservices
•
Enables stand-alone applications with embedded servers
•
Simplifies configuration with auto-configuration and sensible defaults
•
Integrates with Spring Cloud for service discovery, load balancing, etc.
•
Offers a rich ecosystem of libraries and modules
•
Provides flexibility, modularity, and developer productivity
•
Supports containerization for modern deployment environments

SpringBootApplication @SpringBootA pplication public class DemoWebApplication { public static void main(String[] args) { SpringA pplication.run(DemoWebA pplication.class, args); }

SpringBootApplicatin & Controller
•
Use controller for REST API for communications
@RestController
public class GreetingController {
@GetMapping("/greeting")
public String greeting(@RequestParam(value = "name", 
defaultValue = "World") String name) {
return "Hello, " + name + "!";
}
}

Spring Initialzr
•
Commonly used to generate SpringBoot Project
•
Web-based tool for generating Spring Boot projects
•
Accessible at https://start.spring.io
•
Offer Customizable project setup
•
Simplifies dependency management (e.g. Eureka Server, Spring Web) 
and generates a ready-to-import project
•
Enhance developer productivity

RestAPI

What is REST?
•
REST: Representational State Transfer
•
Architectural style for designing networked applications
•
Uses HTTP as the foundation for communication
•
Relies on standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
•
Leverages resource-based URLs for identification
•
Supports multiple data formats (e.g., JSON, XML)
•
Statelessness ensures scalability and maintainability

REST API Principles
•
Resources: Key entities/objects in the system (e.g., users, 
products)
•
Stateless: Each request is independent, no server-side state 
management
•
Cacheability: Responses can be cached to improve 
performance
•
Client-Server: Separation of concerns between UI and 
backend logic
•
Layered System: Enables modular architecture with clear 
boundaries
•
Code on Demand (optional): Server can extend client 
functionality

RESET API example
•
URL: 
https://api.example.com/products
•
HTTP Method: GET
•
Request Headers: Accept: 
application/json
•
Response Status: 200 OK
•
Response Headers: Content-Type: 
application/json
•
Response Body (JSON):
ETO & pprices:]1500) oP HBL Ta SMI 200}

REST Reousrce Identification
•
Resources are central components in REST architecture
•
Represent entities or objects in the system (e.g., users, 
products)
•
Resource identification using URIs
•
Unique and descriptive URIs assigned to each resource
•
Hierarchical structure for easy organization (e.g., 
/products/1, /users/2)

REST Resource Identification
•
Accessing resources using HTTP methods
•
Standard HTTP methods map to CRUD operations:
•
GET: Retrieve a resource or a collection of resources
•
POST: Create a new resource
•
PUT: Update an existing resource
•
DELETE: Remove a resource
•
Collections and individual resources
•
Collections represent a group of resources (e.g., /products)
•
Individual resources are specific instances within a collection 
(e.g., /products/1)

Interacting with Resources
HTTP requests and responses
Clients interact with resources by sending HTTP requests to the 
server
Server processes requests and returns HTTP responses
Request components
Method: GET, POST, PUT, or DELETE
URI: The target resource''s URI (e.g., 
https://api.example.com/products/1)
Headers: Metadata (e.g., Content-Type, Accept)
Body: Payload, if applicable (e.g., JSON or XML data)

Interacting with Resources
Response components
Status: Indicates the outcome (e.g., 200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad 
Request)
Headers: Metadata (e.g., Content-Type, Cache-Control)
Body: Resource representation or error details, if applicable
Resource representations
Resources can be represented in multiple formats (e.g., JSON, 
XML)
Clients and servers negotiate the format using the Accept and 
Content-Type headers

