INSERT INTO parsed_documents (document_name, document_hash, parsed_json, summary, chunks, concepts, relationships, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at, modules, source_id, raw_text) VALUES ( '9-3_NamingServerAndWebClient.pdf', 'f3e0e48674b25417b2ed125f729b96c971270e51ab3f496b5ca1dfed96494fce', '{"chunks": [{"id": "CHUNK_001", "text": "Eureka naming server implements a network service for responding to queries against a directory service. It is a REST-based server used in AWS Cloud services providing load balancing and failover of middle-tier services. Also known as Discovery Server, it is part of the Spring Cloud bundle with a default port of 8761. The server holds information about all client service applications, registering clients with their port numbers and IP addresses while providing interactive services for eureka clients.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 610, "summary": "Definition and technical specifications of the Eureka Naming Server.", "start_pos": 0, "chunk_type": "definition", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_001"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": []}, {"id": "CHUNK_002", "text": "Service registration and service discovery are core processes enabled by Eureka. All microservices register with the Eureka naming server, a process called Service Registration. The naming server provides instances of services currently running, and this process is called Service Discovery. When a microservice needs to communicate with another, it discovers the target service with the help of the Eureka Server. This acts as a common medium enabling communication among all microservices in the application.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 1200, "summary": "Detailed explanation of registration and discovery mechanisms.", "start_pos": 611, "chunk_type": "process_explanation", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_002", "CONC_003"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_003", "text": "In a school scenario example, a naming server is set up with three registered microservices: student-service, module-service, and admission-service. All services register to the naming server. The Admission service must ensure access to the student and module services. This demonstrates communication happening among multiple microservices. The system status shows registered instances with specific IPs and ports, ensuring the Admission service shows modules and student information obtained from respective services.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 1850, "summary": "School scenario demonstrating multi-service interaction.", "start_pos": 1201, "chunk_type": "scenario", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_001"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_002"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_004", "text": "To enable the Eureka Server, Java code uses @EnableEurekaServer annotation and sets server.port=8761. To enable the Eureka Client, the application acts as a discovery client using configuration files like application.yml. Settings indicate the server runs on port 8761. The Eureka Server cannot register itself, nor fetch registry data as it holds the registry. Configuration involves specific package names and annotations to initialize SpringApplication for microservices acting as server or client.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 2450, "summary": "Technical implementation steps for Server and Client configurations.", "start_pos": 1851, "chunk_type": "implementation", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_006", "CONC_001"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_003"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_005", "text": "WebClient is a non-blocking, reactive HTTP client introduced in Spring WebFlux (Spring Framework 5). It provides a modern functional programming API for HTTP requests, replacing RestTemplate for reactive and non-blocking applications. It supports reactive programming with Flux and Mono types from Project Reactor. Key features include filtering, custom error handling, and request/response transformation capabilities suitable for modern enterprise architectures.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 3100, "summary": "Introduction and feature overview of the WebClient component.", "start_pos": 2451, "chunk_type": "definition", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_004"], "has_definitions": true, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_006", "text": "Creating a WebClient uses builder() or create() methods to configure base URLs and headers. Performing HTTP requests supports GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, URI templating, and content negotiation. WebClient returns Mono or Flux for asynchronous processing. Error handling uses onErrorReturn or onErrorResume. Integration with Spring Cloud components allows service discovery and load balancing. Advanced capabilities include backpressure support and resource management.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 3750, "summary": "Usage patterns and capabilities of the WebClient class.", "start_pos": 3101, "chunk_type": "tutorial", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_004"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_001"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_007", "text": "Executing the microservice application involves starting the Eureka Server first, then Provider Applications (student-module), followed by the Consumer Application (admission). Testing involves accessing URLs like /actuator/info or /admission/modules. Users can modify URL paths to check availability or use Postman to register students. The Admission service retrieves module and student information from downstream services, displaying JSON responses confirming successful inter-service calls.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 4400, "summary": "Step-by-step execution and testing guide for the application.", "start_pos": 3751, "chunk_type": "testing_guide", "has_examples": true, "main_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_003"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_002"]}, {"id": "CHUNK_008", "text": "Wrap up summarizes Microservices vs monolithic applications. Spring Boot creates standalone mini servers. Controllers map URLs to functions similar to HttpServlet. The Eureka Server acts as the naming server for service discovery. REST API + JSON serves as the communication standard. WebClient handles HTTP connections. References provided link to external resources detailing registration, discovery, and best practices for Netflix Eureka integration.", "pages": [1], "end_pos": 4900, "summary": "High-level summary and reference section of the course material.", "start_pos": 4401, "chunk_type": "summary", "has_examples": false, "main_concepts": ["CONC_005", "CONC_001", "CONC_004"], "has_definitions": false, "secondary_concepts": ["CONC_006"]}], "concepts": [{"id": "CONC_001", "title": "Eureka Naming Server", "aliases": ["Eureka Server", "Naming Server", "Service Registry"], "keywords": ["REST", "Discovery Server", "Registry", "AWS", "Port 8761"], "confidence": 0.95, "difficulty": 3, "description": "A REST-based server implementation used in AWS Cloud services for load balancing and failover of middle-tier services. Also known as the Discovery Server, it holds information about all client service applications including their port numbers and IP addresses. It functions as a central registry where each microservice registers itself to enable communication within the application architecture.", "concept_type": "component", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_001", "CHUNK_002"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_002", "CONC_003"]}, {"id": "CONC_002", "title": "Service Discovery", "aliases": ["Service Lookup", "Instance Registration Query"], "keywords": ["Instance Discovery", "Routing", "Query", "Network Resolution"], "confidence": 0.95, "difficulty": 3, "description": "The process by which a naming server provides the instances of a service that are currently running to other services. When a microservice needs to communicate with another, it queries the Eureka Server to discover available instances via Service Discovery mechanisms. This decouples services from hard-coded network addresses.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_002"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_004"]}, {"id": "CONC_003", "title": "Service Registration", "aliases": ["Server Registration", "Service Bind"], "keywords": ["Auto-registration", "Directory Service", "Client Registration"], "confidence": 0.95, "difficulty": 2, "description": "The action where all microservices register themselves with the Eureka naming server. This registration includes details such as port numbers and IP addresses. Without this step, the discovery mechanism cannot locate the service instance. It is a prerequisite for any microservice wishing to participate in the distributed system network.", "concept_type": "process", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_002", "CHUNK_003"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001"]}, {"id": "CONC_004", "title": "WebClient", "aliases": ["Spring WebClient"], "keywords": ["Reactive", "Non-blocking", "Mono", "Flux", "HTTP Client"], "confidence": 0.95, "difficulty": 4, "description": "A non-blocking, reactive HTTP client introduced in Spring WebFlux (Spring Framework 5). It provides a modern functional programming API for performing HTTP requests, replacing RestTemplate for reactive applications. It supports Flux and Mono types for asynchronous processing, backpressure support, and advanced features like request filtering and error handling.", "concept_type": "object", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_005", "CHUNK_006"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_002", "CONC_005"]}, {"id": "CONC_005", "title": "Microservices Architecture", "aliases": ["Microservices Pattern", "Distributed Services"], "keywords": ["Decoupling", "Independent Deployment", "Scalability", "REST API"], "confidence": 0.9, "difficulty": 3, "description": "An architectural style structuring an application as a collection of loosely coupled services. Unlike monolithic applications, these services implement business capabilities independently. They communicate over standard protocols like REST APIs using JSON, enabling independent deployment and scaling. Examples include student-service, module-service, and admission-service working together.", "concept_type": "architecture", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_003", "CHUNK_007", "CHUNK_008"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_004"]}, {"id": "CONC_006", "title": "Spring Boot", "aliases": ["Spring Boot Application"], "keywords": ["Standalone", "Mini Server", "Configuration", "Rest Controller"], "confidence": 0.95, "difficulty": 3, "description": "A framework used to create stand-alone applications and mini servers. It simplifies the setup of Spring Framework projects. In the context of microservices, it enables applications to run as controllers or rest controllers mapping URLs to functions. It acts as the foundation for running the Eureka Server and Client configurations.", "concept_type": "component", "extracted_from": ["CHUNK_004", "CHUNK_008"], "related_concepts": ["CONC_001", "CONC_005"]}], "relationships": [{"id": "REL_001", "type": "implements", "source": "CONC_001", "target": "CONC_002", "evidence": "Eureka Server is also known as Discovery Server providing instances of service.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_002", "type": "managed_by", "source": "CONC_003", "target": "CONC_001", "evidence": "All microservices will be registered with the Eureka naming server.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_003", "type": "consumes", "source": "CONC_004", "target": "CONC_002", "evidence": "WebClient is used to discover other microservice with the help of Eureka Server.", "strength": 0.9, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_004", "type": "requires", "source": "CONC_005", "target": "CONC_001", "evidence": "Eureka naming server is common medium that enables communication among all microservices.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": true}, {"id": "REL_005", "type": "hosting", "source": "CONC_006", "target": "CONC_001", "evidence": "Make your application/microservice acts as a Eureka discovery server using SpringApplication.", "strength": 1.0, "bidirectional": false}, {"id": "REL_006", "type": "enables_communication", "source": "CONC_004", "target": "CONC_005", "evidence": "WebClient provides a modern API for performing HTTP requests between microservices.", "strength": 0.9, "bidirectional": false}], "quality_metrics": {"total_chunks": 8, "missing_links": [], "coverage_score": 0.95, "total_concepts": 6, "consistency_score": 0.98, "total_relationships": 6}, "document_metadata": {"title": "Naming Server & Web Client ITP4511", "language": "English", "main_topic": "Enterprise System Development - Eureka & WebClient", "difficulty_level": "Intermediate", "estimated_reading_time": "15 minutes"}, "concept_chunk_mapping": [{"concept": "Eureka Naming Server", "context": "Primary subject definition.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_001", "positions": [0, 120], "concept_id": "CONC_001", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Service Discovery", "context": "Core process definition.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_002", "positions": [0, 45], "concept_id": "CONC_002", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Service Registration", "context": "Process detailed in mechanism.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_002", "positions": [120, 150], "concept_id": "CONC_003", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Microservices Architecture", "context": "Example scenario application.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_003", "positions": [20, 40], "concept_id": "CONC_005", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Spring Boot", "context": "Implementation platform.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_004", "positions": [50, 80], "concept_id": "CONC_006", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "WebClient", "context": "Component introduction.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_005", "positions": [0, 20], "concept_id": "CONC_004", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Microservices Architecture", "context": "Execution verification.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_007", "positions": [20, 45], "concept_id": "CONC_005", "importance": "primary"}, {"concept": "Eureka Naming Server", "context": "Summary recap.", "chunk_id": "CHUNK_008", "positions": [100, 130], "concept_id": "CONC_001", "importance": "secondary"}]}', '{"total_modules": 4, "total_concepts": 12, "difficulty_score": 6, "total_structures": 6, "total_applications": 8}', '"[{\"id\":\"CHUNK_001\",\"text\":\"Eureka naming server implements a network service for responding to queries against a directory service. It is a REST-based server used in AWS Cloud services providing load balancing and failover of middle-tier services. Also known as Discovery Server, it is part of the Spring Cloud bundle with a default port of 8761. The server holds information about all client service applications, registering clients with their port numbers and IP addresses while providing interactive services for eureka clients.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":0,\"end_pos\":610,\"summary\":\"Definition and technical specifications of the Eureka Naming Server.\",\"chunk_type\":\"definition\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_002\",\"text\":\"Service registration and service discovery are core processes enabled by Eureka. All microservices register with the Eureka naming server, a process called Service Registration. The naming server provides instances of services currently running, and this process is called Service Discovery. When a microservice needs to communicate with another, it discovers the target service with the help of the Eureka Server. This acts as a common medium enabling communication among all microservices in the application.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":611,\"end_pos\":1200,\"summary\":\"Detailed explanation of registration and discovery mechanisms.\",\"chunk_type\":\"process_explanation\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_003\",\"text\":\"In a school scenario example, a naming server is set up with three registered microservices: student-service, module-service, and admission-service. All services register to the naming server. The Admission service must ensure access to the student and module services. This demonstrates communication happening among multiple microservices. The system status shows registered instances with specific IPs and ports, ensuring the Admission service shows modules and student information obtained from respective services.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":1201,\"end_pos\":1850,\"summary\":\"School scenario demonstrating multi-service interaction.\",\"chunk_type\":\"scenario\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_001\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_004\",\"text\":\"To enable the Eureka Server, Java code uses @EnableEurekaServer annotation and sets server.port=8761. To enable the Eureka Client, the application acts as a discovery client using configuration files like application.yml. Settings indicate the server runs on port 8761. The Eureka Server cannot register itself, nor fetch registry data as it holds the registry. Configuration involves specific package names and annotations to initialize SpringApplication for microservices acting as server or client.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":1851,\"end_pos\":2450,\"summary\":\"Technical implementation steps for Server and Client configurations.\",\"chunk_type\":\"implementation\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_006\",\"CONC_001\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_003\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_005\",\"text\":\"WebClient is a non-blocking, reactive HTTP client introduced in Spring WebFlux (Spring Framework 5). It provides a modern functional programming API for HTTP requests, replacing RestTemplate for reactive and non-blocking applications. It supports reactive programming with Flux and Mono types from Project Reactor. Key features include filtering, custom error handling, and request/response transformation capabilities suitable for modern enterprise architectures.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":2451,\"end_pos\":3100,\"summary\":\"Introduction and feature overview of the WebClient component.\",\"chunk_type\":\"definition\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_004\"],\"has_definitions\":true,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_006\",\"text\":\"Creating a WebClient uses builder() or create() methods to configure base URLs and headers. Performing HTTP requests supports GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, URI templating, and content negotiation. WebClient returns Mono or Flux for asynchronous processing. Error handling uses onErrorReturn or onErrorResume. Integration with Spring Cloud components allows service discovery and load balancing. Advanced capabilities include backpressure support and resource management.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":3101,\"end_pos\":3750,\"summary\":\"Usage patterns and capabilities of the WebClient class.\",\"chunk_type\":\"tutorial\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_004\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_007\",\"text\":\"Executing the microservice application involves starting the Eureka Server first, then Provider Applications (student-module), followed by the Consumer Application (admission). Testing involves accessing URLs like /actuator/info or /admission/modules. Users can modify URL paths to check availability or use Postman to register students. The Admission service retrieves module and student information from downstream services, displaying JSON responses confirming successful inter-service calls.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":3751,\"end_pos\":4400,\"summary\":\"Step-by-step execution and testing guide for the application.\",\"chunk_type\":\"testing_guide\",\"has_examples\":true,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_003\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\"]},{\"id\":\"CHUNK_008\",\"text\":\"Wrap up summarizes Microservices vs monolithic applications. Spring Boot creates standalone mini servers. Controllers map URLs to functions similar to HttpServlet. The Eureka Server acts as the naming server for service discovery. REST API + JSON serves as the communication standard. WebClient handles HTTP connections. References provided link to external resources detailing registration, discovery, and best practices for Netflix Eureka integration.\",\"pages\":[1],\"start_pos\":4401,\"end_pos\":4900,\"summary\":\"High-level summary and reference section of the course material.\",\"chunk_type\":\"summary\",\"has_examples\":false,\"main_concepts\":[\"CONC_005\",\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_004\"],\"has_definitions\":false,\"secondary_concepts\":[\"CONC_006\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"CONC_001\",\"title\":\"Eureka Naming Server\",\"aliases\":[\"Eureka Server\",\"Naming Server\",\"Service Registry\"],\"keywords\":[\"REST\",\"Discovery Server\",\"Registry\",\"AWS\",\"Port 8761\"],\"confidence\":0.95,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A REST-based server implementation used in AWS Cloud services for load balancing and failover of middle-tier services. Also known as the Discovery Server, it holds information about all client service applications including their port numbers and IP addresses. It functions as a central registry where each microservice registers itself to enable communication within the application architecture.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_001\",\"CHUNK_002\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_003\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_002\",\"title\":\"Service Discovery\",\"aliases\":[\"Service Lookup\",\"Instance Registration Query\"],\"keywords\":[\"Instance Discovery\",\"Routing\",\"Query\",\"Network Resolution\"],\"confidence\":0.95,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"The process by which a naming server provides the instances of a service that are currently running to other services. When a microservice needs to communicate with another, it queries the Eureka Server to discover available instances via Service Discovery mechanisms. This decouples services from hard-coded network addresses.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_002\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_004\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_003\",\"title\":\"Service Registration\",\"aliases\":[\"Server Registration\",\"Service Bind\"],\"keywords\":[\"Auto-registration\",\"Directory Service\",\"Client Registration\"],\"confidence\":0.95,\"difficulty\":2,\"description\":\"The action where all microservices register themselves with the Eureka naming server. This registration includes details such as port numbers and IP addresses. Without this step, the discovery mechanism cannot locate the service instance. It is a prerequisite for any microservice wishing to participate in the distributed system network.\",\"concept_type\":\"process\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_002\",\"CHUNK_003\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_004\",\"title\":\"WebClient\",\"aliases\":[\"Spring WebClient\"],\"keywords\":[\"Reactive\",\"Non-blocking\",\"Mono\",\"Flux\",\"HTTP Client\"],\"confidence\":0.95,\"difficulty\":4,\"description\":\"A non-blocking, reactive HTTP client introduced in Spring WebFlux (Spring Framework 5). It provides a modern functional programming API for performing HTTP requests, replacing RestTemplate for reactive applications. It supports Flux and Mono types for asynchronous processing, backpressure support, and advanced features like request filtering and error handling.\",\"concept_type\":\"object\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_005\",\"CHUNK_006\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_002\",\"CONC_005\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_005\",\"title\":\"Microservices Architecture\",\"aliases\":[\"Microservices Pattern\",\"Distributed Services\"],\"keywords\":[\"Decoupling\",\"Independent Deployment\",\"Scalability\",\"REST API\"],\"confidence\":0.9,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"An architectural style structuring an application as a collection of loosely coupled services. Unlike monolithic applications, these services implement business capabilities independently. They communicate over standard protocols like REST APIs using JSON, enabling independent deployment and scaling. Examples include student-service, module-service, and admission-service working together.\",\"concept_type\":\"architecture\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_003\",\"CHUNK_007\",\"CHUNK_008\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_004\"]},{\"id\":\"CONC_006\",\"title\":\"Spring Boot\",\"aliases\":[\"Spring Boot Application\"],\"keywords\":[\"Standalone\",\"Mini Server\",\"Configuration\",\"Rest Controller\"],\"confidence\":0.95,\"difficulty\":3,\"description\":\"A framework used to create stand-alone applications and mini servers. It simplifies the setup of Spring Framework projects. In the context of microservices, it enables applications to run as controllers or rest controllers mapping URLs to functions. It acts as the foundation for running the Eureka Server and Client configurations.\",\"concept_type\":\"component\",\"extracted_from\":[\"CHUNK_004\",\"CHUNK_008\"],\"related_concepts\":[\"CONC_001\",\"CONC_005\"]}]"', '"[{\"id\":\"REL_001\",\"type\":\"implements\",\"source\":\"CONC_001\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"Eureka Server is also known as Discovery Server providing instances of service.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_002\",\"type\":\"managed_by\",\"source\":\"CONC_003\",\"target\":\"CONC_001\",\"evidence\":\"All microservices will be registered with the Eureka naming server.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_003\",\"type\":\"consumes\",\"source\":\"CONC_004\",\"target\":\"CONC_002\",\"evidence\":\"WebClient is used to discover other microservice with the help of Eureka Server.\",\"strength\":0.9,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_004\",\"type\":\"requires\",\"source\":\"CONC_005\",\"target\":\"CONC_001\",\"evidence\":\"Eureka naming server is common medium that enables communication among all microservices.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":true},{\"id\":\"REL_005\",\"type\":\"hosting\",\"source\":\"CONC_006\",\"target\":\"CONC_001\",\"evidence\":\"Make your application/microservice acts as a Eureka discovery server using SpringApplication.\",\"strength\":1,\"bidirectional\":false},{\"id\":\"REL_006\",\"type\":\"enables_communication\",\"source\":\"CONC_004\",\"target\":\"CONC_005\",\"evidence\":\"WebClient provides a modern API for performing HTTP requests between microservices.\",\"strength\":0.9,\"bidirectional\":false}]"', '2026-04-28 06:37:04.518996', '2026-04-28 06:37:04.518996', NULL, '[{"id": "module_1", "name": "Eureka Naming Server Overview", "topic_count": 6}, {"id": "module_2", "name": "Service Registration and Discovery", "topic_count": 4}, {"id": "module_3", "name": "WebClient for Reactive HTTP", "topic_count": 5}, {"id": "module_4", "name": "Microservices Communication Example", "topic_count": 6}]', NULL, 'Naming Server & Web Client ITP4511 — Enterprise System Development

Eureka naming server
•
The naming server implements a network service for responding to queries against a directory 
service.
•
Eureka naming server
•
is a REST-based server 
•
is used in the AWS Cloud services providing load balancing and failover of middle-tier services.
•
also known as Discovery Server.
•
the bundle of Spring Cloud. 
•
default port 8761
•
holds information about all client service applications. 
•
Each microservice registers itself with the Eureka naming server.  The naming server registers the 
client services with their port numbers and IP addresses. 
•
Provide interactive services for eureka client

Eureka naming server
•
is common medium that enables communication among all 
microservices in an application,
•
hold have details of all microservices in the application. 
•
All microservices will register with Eureka Server as a discovery 
client. When a microservice needs to communicate with the 
other microservice, it will discover other microservice with the 
help of Eureka Server.

Service registration and service 
discovery
•
Service Discovery.
•
All microservices will be register with the Eureka naming server. The 
registration of microservice with the naming server is called Service 
Registration.
•
Service Discovery  
•
The naming server provides the instances of service that are 
currently running. The process of providing instances to other 
services is called Service Discovery.

Microservices example in School 
Scenario 
•
A naming sever is 
setup 
•
Three microservices 
are registered
•
student-service
•
module-service
•
admission-service
•
All services are 
registered to the 
naming server
•
Admission service 
make sure of the 
student service and 
module services
Demonstrate the communication happen among multiple microservices
